abstract: The Flynn deal opens the door to charges against the president’s inner circle — and his family.
snippet: The Flynn deal opens the door to charges against the president’s inner circle — and his family.
lead_paragraph: On Friday morning, Michael Flynn pleaded guilty to lying to the F.B.I. while serving as President Trump’s national security adviser. Making a false statement to a federal official is a felony offense, but nowhere near as bad as what the special counsel, Robert Mueller, could likely have charged Mr. Flynn with, including charges for possible violations of the Foreign Agents Registration Act (similar to those brought against the former Trump campaign chairman Paul Manafort and his deputy Rick Gates) or those stemming from a possible attempt to kidnap a Turkish cleric in Pennsylvania. By pleading guilty and agreeing to cooperate with Mr. Mueller, Mr. Flynn also appears to have averted prosecution of his son, who was reportedly implicated in some of the misconduct.

abstract: It’s a big city, with plenty to do, see, hear and watch. Here’s a sampling of cultural highlights this weekend and over the week ahead.
snippet: It’s a big city, with plenty to do, see, hear and watch. Here’s a sampling of cultural highlights this weekend and over the week ahead.
lead_paragraph: This troupe, led by Eduardo Vilaro, returns to the Apollo on Friday and Saturday at 8 p.m., with three works, including Michelle Manzanales’s “Con Brazos Abiertos” (“With Open Arms”), a playful look at her Mexican-American childhood in Texas from 2017. What was it like to be caught between cultures? In “Espiritu Vivo” (2012), Ronald K. Brown explores grief and finds inspiration in the meeting of African and Latino diasporas in the Caribbean and Latin America. And the Spanish choreographer Ramón Oller offers “Bury Me Standing,” from 1998, which touches on Gypsy culture. GIA KOURLAS

abstract: In a reshuffling of Mayor Bill de Blasio’s cabinet, the first deputy mayor, Anthony E. Shorris, said that he is leaving City Hall.
snippet: In a reshuffling of Mayor Bill de Blasio’s cabinet, the first deputy mayor, Anthony E. Shorris, said that he is leaving City Hall.
lead_paragraph: The first deputy mayor of New York City, Anthony E. Shorris, said on Wednesday that he was leaving the administration, a move that marks the first major reshuffling of Mayor Bill de Blasio’s inner circle as he prepares for a second term.

abstract: What did Matt Lauer, Charlie Rose and Bill O’Reilly have in common? They were encouraged to be larger-than-life characters before their sudden falls.
snippet: What did Matt Lauer, Charlie Rose and Bill O’Reilly have in common? They were encouraged to be larger-than-life characters before their sudden falls.
lead_paragraph: Matt Lauer, of NBC News, played the easygoing dad you could rely on — fun-loving but serious enough when he had to be.

abstract: Write-in votes, a kind of protest against the listed candidates, soared in 2017 to more than 5,000, far higher than in recent mayoral elections.
snippet: Write-in votes, a kind of protest against the listed candidates, soared in 2017 to more than 5,000, far higher than in recent mayoral elections.
lead_paragraph: In an election year marked by lackluster campaigning and low turnout, one group of New York City voters came to the polls in droves: those seeking to lodge the futile and time-honored protest of writing in a candidate for mayor.

abstract: Though the sculpture emerged from the smoldering ruins largely intact and became a symbol of resilience, it was unwelcome at the memorial for years.
snippet: Though the sculpture emerged from the smoldering ruins largely intact and became a symbol of resilience, it was unwelcome at the memorial for years.
lead_paragraph: The memorial at Pearl Harbor captures terror and loss by allowing visitors to view the destroyed U.S.S. Arizona under the sea. The memorial at Hiroshima makes a statement about death and hope by preserving the ruins of a domed hall that stood at the atomic bomb’s hypocenter. But in New York, the 9/11 Memorial had no such authentic artifact on the site to remind visitors of the horror of the attack it commemorated.

abstract: For decades, the plan to reduce traffic by charging drivers in crowded zones in Manhattan has been revived again and again.
snippet: For decades, the plan to reduce traffic by charging drivers in crowded zones in Manhattan has been revived again and again.
lead_paragraph: It is the Lazarus of congestion plans: reduce traffic in New York City by charging drivers in crowded areas at peak traffic times.
